{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491370"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:44:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:44:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"924"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/924"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.07,0.02,0.1,0.69]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"924"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43265"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/924"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"924"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28255"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"435"},{"type":"tags","id":"2076"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1095"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1158"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43974"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43265"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with three days of painless loss of vision in the right eye. The symptoms came on suddenly. He has a medical history of coronary artery ischaemia for which he had a drug-eluting stent inserted one year ago. His medications include clopidogrel. On examination, he appears well. Visual acuity is 6/6 in the left eye and at counting fingers in the right eye. Fundoscopy is performed and the retina appears as shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Central retinal artery occlusion","Retinal detachment","Non-proliferative diabetic retinopathy","Hypertensive retinopathy","Central retinal vein occlusion"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe fundus shows evidence of flame haemorrhages throughout the retina with white cotton wool spots representing areas of infarction. This appearance is consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Ecentral retinal vein occlusion\u003C/strong\u003E. This patient needs specialist eye treatment with anti-vascular endothelial growth factor (anti-VEGF) to prevent neovascularisation of the iris that causes painful intractable glaucoma in a blind eye. His General Practitioner needs to manage his vascular risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECentral retinal artery occlusion\u003C/strong\u003E may also present with sudden painless vision loss, however the fundus is likely to be pale with a cherry red spot at the macula. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Cstrong\u003Eretinal detachment\u003C/strong\u003E the fundus will have a \u0027crinkling\u0027 appearance with an associated tear or hole. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-proliferative diabetic retinopathy \u003C/strong\u003Eand\u003Cstrong\u003E hypertensive retinopathy\u003C/strong\u003E may present with more gradual vision loss.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Central retinal vein occlusion is an important cause of rapidly progressive visual loss."],"references":["Scott IU, Campochiaro PA, Newman NJ, et al.  Retinal Vascular Occlusions. Lancet. 2020; 396: 1927\u201340."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28255"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions"